cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this specification, please cite it as below."
type: software
title: "Agent Context Memory: A Governance-First Specification for AI Agent Context Memory"
abstract: >
  ACM (Agent Context Memory) is a specification for governance-first context memory
  in autonomous AI agent systems. It recognizes that agent memory is fundamentally
  an authorization problem and applies established access control patterns — the
  "authorization before action" principle common to RBAC, MAC, and capability-based
  security — to this domain. The core contribution is the Mandate Gate:
  a pre-work mandate, authored by the principal, must exist in the agent's memory
  before any session of work is valid. Prior models (MemGPT, CoALA, Generative Agents)
  treat memory as a working resource the agent draws from during work. ACM treats
  memory as a precondition — the gate that determines whether work can begin at all.
  ACM also defines three memory tiers organized by trust level (intent / trace /
  evidence), structural capture-author separation, and convergence as a memory-level
  property. ACM is the operationalization of Principles of Earned Autonomy (PEA)
  for the context memory design problem. The reference implementation is the
  .trail/ directory pattern, publicly released April 24, 2026 (DOI: 10.5281/zenodo.19732827)
  before this specification was written.
